result.execSummary:
The defendant Benjamin J Jackson was found guilty of the following charge(s) in this case. One or more other charges in this case were dismissed. The dismissed charges were not proven and have no legal effect. Benjamin J Jackson is presumed innocent of the dismissed charges.

  • Benjamin J Jackson was found guilty of Child Abuse-Recklessly Cause Harm, a class I felony, Wisconsin Statutes 948.03(3)(b).
  • Benjamin J Jackson was found guilty of Neglecting a Child (Consequence is Great Bodily Harm), a class F felony, Wisconsin Statutes 948.21(1)(c).

Notice to employers: It may be a violation of state law to discriminate against a job applicant because of an arrest or conviction record. Generally speaking, an employer may refuse to hire an applicant on the basis of a conviction only if the circumstances of the conviction substantially relate to the particular job. For more information, see Wisconsin Statute 111.335 and the Department of Workforce Development's publication, Arrest and Conviction Records under the Law.

Defendant Benjamin J Jackson in court with attorney Matt Last.  Defendant Benjamin J Jackson in custody.  Matthew James Torbenson appeared for the State of Wisconsin.  
Deputy Court Clerk: rmm.  
Court found the state has satisfied victims' rights law.  Statements by each counsel and defendant as to sentencing.  Additional statements made by:  Rosalinda O., Beth T., Candace O. and Donna E. 
AS TO COUNT 2;  Court sentenced defendant to serve a Term of Imprisonment of 3 YEARS 6 MONTHS in the Wisconsin State Prison, consecutive to any other sentence; credit for 252 days served.  Court ordered 1 YEAR 6 MONTHS Initial Term Of Confinement and 2 YEARS Extended Supervision.
.
AS TO COUNT 3;  Court sentenced defendant to serve a Term of Imprisonment of 7 YEARS in the Wisconsin State Prison, concurrent with Count 2; credit for 252 days served.  Court ordered 2 YEARS Initial Term Of Confinement and 5 YEARS Extended Supervision.

Court found defendant not eligible for Challenge Incarceration or Earned Release Programs.

Conditions of Extended Supervision:
- No further violations of the law.
- Mental health assessment; received treatment.
- Cooperate with the MBCW.
- Complete a course in anger management.
- Attend parenting classes.
- Complete a nurturing class.
- Mental health evaluation; take all prescribed medications.
- AODA assessment; comply with any treatment.
- Maintain absolute sobriety; random urine screens.
- Attend treatment and/or counseling as determined.
- No unsupervised contact with victim unless approved by the Court, then if contact is allowed, NO VIOLENT CONTACT.
- Obtain/maintain employment.
- No contact with firearms.
- Pay all costs, surcharges and supervision fees.
- Court set restitution at zero.
 
Received and filed: Pretrial Sentence Credit, Notice of Right to Seek Post-Conviction Relief, Written Explanation of Determinate Sentence. 
.
Court advised defendant of penalties for violating the no contact order.  Court advised defendant that as a convicted felon s/he must provide a DNA sample, his/her voting rights are suspended and s/he may never possess firearms.  The Court ordered that all court costs, fines, surcharges and/or restitution be paid through collection by the Department of Corrections from 25% of funds under Sec. 973.05(4)(b) and as a condition of extended supervision. DOC shall collect those sums.  Any amount remaining due and owing is subject to civil judgment and/or tax intercept or other means.
